Cuccinelli (R), the state attorney general, now trails businessman Terry McAuliffe (D) by 12 points among likely voters, the survey shows. And Cuccinelli’s decline comes as Virginians are increasingly turned off by the movement that has backed him strongly and with which he shares many views. McAuliffe opens 12-point lead against Cuccinelli in Va. The Democrat is in position to break the Va. pattern of voting against the party that controls the White House. Read more The tea party is now opposed by 53 percent of registered voters in the commonwealth, Independents have soured most dramatically on the tea party: Fifty-five percent of them now oppose the movement, up from 37 percent in May 2011. The tea party is also opposed by 80 percent of Democrats and 23 percent of Republicans. The tea party’s slippage hasn’t stopped Cuccinelli from running a campaign increasingly focused on turning out base Republican voters in the final weeks of an off-year election in which turnout is expected to be low. Cuccinelli’s increasingly narrow path to victory requires his base to vote in droves while McAuliffe’s stays home. Yet conservatives don’t appear to be winning the enthusiasm battle. While 83 percent of strong tea party supporters say they are certain to vote, 78 percent of strong tea party opponents — a much larger group — say the same.
